generation: Summer TV used to be a wasteland of repeats, but now two exciting new shows have captured my attention. 'Blow Out' is a wildly creative concept that defies expectations with its all-star cast. Jonothan Antin, the renowned hairstylist, is expanding his popular West Hollywood salon to Beverly Hills, much to the delight of his loyal followers. I can't get enough of his larger-than-life personality and grandiose plans for the new location. It's been a while since I've found a character as captivating as Rocco, and Jonothan is quickly becoming my new obsession.

This week, I have been experiencing discomfort in my right shoulder due to tendonitis. The inflammation is located just under my shoulder blade, and it becomes particularly bothersome when I perform repetitive tasks, such as using a computer mouse. My range of motion has been limited as a result, and I am finding it challenging to move my arm freely.
I have been dealing with this issue for some time now, and it has been exacerbated by my recent spree of updating my website and working on other online tasks. I am not able to move my arm as much as I would like to due to the pain, and lack of sleep has only made the situation more challenging. Fortunately, my mother's surgery went well, and her eyesight has partially returned. She is able to make out fuzzy shapes and colors, but she remains blind in all other respects. I hope that her vision will fully recover soon.

Kindness of strangers... Attempted laundry today with kids in tow and realized how quickly simple tasks can become a frustrating ordeal. I also learned how sweet total strangers can be for no reason other than to be kind. Trust me, it wasn't like they were trying to get in my pants. I had kid drool all over me and was wearing my 'wash-day' outfit... I'm not sure I'll ever bathe again, so there was no olfactory incentive there! I am currently composing a post and watching the Collected No Doubt videos. I am doing both of these things from my desk in my room.

It's 11:14 PM and I'm in my bedroom, fixing the personal computer of my boss. While I enjoy helping others with their technology, I wonder if I'm being taken advantage of. The past couple of weeks have been busy, so I've been staying up late reading and such. I was looking forward to getting some rest, but I realized it would be better to get the computer back to its owner. *laugh* No rest for the weary, I guess. I found myself watching Joe Schmo 2 tonight.

Remind me, what did I write about before this? Or, a continuation in the 'is this a date?' saga. After the weird lunch, my confidence shook, I forgot to tell you guys an important piece of the story. Before Pat shows up to lunch, Dustin starts talking about what a nice guy Pat is and how he's trying to find a girlfriend for him. I'm listening and nodding, realizing that we're talking more about finding Dustin's best friend, a girl, than discussing whatever it is you discuss with a stranger over pink lemonade. I excused myself to the bathroom, looked in the mirror, and silently asked myself: am I being pawned off on the other guy? Is this what happens now?

I would like everyone to think before they act. I'd like each and every single person in the world to think before they get out of bed in the morning and make a commitment to keep thinking all day. If they're not prepared, I'd like them to hop back in bed and drift off to an eternal slumber. I'm sick of stupid people. I'm not the smartest motherfucker in the world... but I'm not talking about things that take a lot of brain power. So, I think it's fair to persecute the inanely stupid. Let's see if I can keep this particular rant to a few particular types, and we'll save some for another day. Sounds good?

I think monopoly has run its course in my life and I vow to never play it again. Tonight Andy beat me by a few small dollars and won the game, or maybe I let him win on account of him leaving in a few short hours and me wanting him to feel good on his last night here. Well, however the story goes, it can't compare to this Texas-sized headache I have at the moment. I've taken some Aleve and I must say they are doing the trick. All I need now is some well-deserved R&R.

Today has been a long day. We had to drive home from Indiana, and I guess I'll have to be choosy about what I write about because I could really take up a lot of time and energy, and I just don't have enough. First off, I have to say that camp was awesome and even better than I could have expected. God has been doing so much stuff in my life lately, and it's just awesome. I've sort of turned over a new leaf, I guess, but anyway, back to the beginning. We arrived at the Twiggs' house on Friday evening and we stayed until we left for camp on Monday. Most of what we did was go to the fair, church, a parade, Walmart, and watched movies.

Arun Shourie highlights how the current Governor of Uttar Pradesh, T.V. Rajeswar, warned of a potential 'third Islamic state' in the subcontinent as far back as 1996. Shourie questions whether Rajeswar's warnings now carry more weight due to his past writings on the topic. Does knowing that Rajeswar, rather than Advani, wrote the warnings make them more credible, or does it raise suspicions about his motives as Governor of Uttar Pradesh?

Last night, I went home and slept off, but only got up when my mother called me around eight thirty. And when I woke up, it was all dark, and I hadn't switched the lights on, so I couldn't figure out what time or date it was, for a few seconds, it was just my mother's voice in the darkness and me grappling with reality. Wonder why I'm feeling so drained. Nice weather this morning. It was drizzling when I came. Although in Calcutta, I hear it's been raining for the past three days.

Last night was the worst. I threw away the sweater I was knitting because it had too many stitches by the time I got to the arm holes, and the mohair was knotting itself together as I knitted. I lost probably $10 worth of yarn, and frogging (ripping out rows) didn't work well. I didn't even swear, which is unusual for me. I just morosely ripped and listened to Season 2 of Sex and the City (way to go, library!). Then I got sick of it and threw it away. I suppose I learned a lot while trying to do this sweater.

Last night in class, we discussed the assigned reading, "Getting Back into Place: Toward a Renewed Study of the Place-World" by Edward S. Casey. The first chapter explores the concept of "implacement" and the second, "displacement." Casey argues that our contemporary world and culture revolve around time as the central force, with a focus on running out of time, saving time, and being just in time. He posits that shifting the center of culture to place can lead to a more grounded community. So far, this book has been the most engaging read thus far.

And while giggling is good, one wonders if we would have found ourselves up that fire escape drinking beer in the fierce wind had we not been eating them earlier. This was a productive weekend. I indulged in various activities, including reading, listening to music, and exploring new books. I completed three books: Bruce Sterling's 'Heavy Weather,' Larry Niven's 'World of Ptavvs,' and Octavia Butler's 'Parable of the Sower.' While I found the stories engaging and well-crafted, I didn't experience any profound emotional resonance. The characters and plot were well-developed, but the books failed to leave a lasting impact. Nonetheless, it was an enjoyable weekend of intellectual exploration.

After returning from practicum, I initially struggled in the first week, but it was only in the second week that the full extent of the trauma became clear. It was a hidden epidemic that only now is coming to light. I was initially burdened by the experience, but speaking with the course coordinator allowed me to release my burden and, in doing so, I prevented another student from suffering the same fate. Yesterday, I encountered another aggrieved classmate who was determined to inform the student who was scheduled to attend the next practicum about the difficulties. I calmed her down and advised her to speak with the administrator first.

Things are hectic here, but I always find time for stress-relieving activities. I'm not great at 8-ball or ping pong, and Rick (the canuck) consistently beats me. We have a ping pong table in our building's front lobby, so I try to squeeze in a quick game whenever I can. Last night, I participated in an 8-ball tournament at our recreation tent, complete with a popcorn machine, TVs, and a ping pong table. Despite scratching on the eight ball, I still had fun, especially when two Dutch soldiers joined in.

Fall 1974: I was trying for what felt like the 13th time to struggle my way through the second chapter of my high school algebra book. I was not then nor am I now a math person. I hate math. I am math phobic. You get the picture. So, as I struggled to make sense of algebra, the doorbell rang. I put down my book and went to open the door. No one was there. Great. I returned to my studies and just as I was finding a little glimmer of understanding buried in my subconscious, the doorbell rang again. Bam, just like that, my breakthrough disappeared. I went to the door and, once again, no one was there. Just what a struggling math student needs, an uninvited practical joker.

This past week has been exhausting. I spent Tuesday through Thursday moving to my new classroom. The new room is bigger and closer to my grade level team, which are the things I need to consider as I spend hours preparing my room for this year. If I knew I was moving before the end of the school year, I would have discarded unnecessary books and supplies. Unfortunately, everything came with me. So, this week was spent moving, unpacking, and purging profusely. I have to thank my teammate Jill for helping with all of this. She was still teaching in my old room, so she and her students moved almost all of my things.

You can't help it, you can't evade it: a piece of you will always live in me. Even if I never carried you child, even if I was never married to you, even if I was never an official pair to you... I loved you immensely, and to this day the feeling carries an echo through my heart. Forever will I always be reminded of the very few nights we spent together, hearts and limbs entwined in a soul-embrace, drenched in the salty darkness of an evening by the beach... Or a kiss under the rain. Whenever I get the feeling of a dark glass puncturing my heart, you will be there. That piece of you... Bleeding the eternal love that once lived in me... And still remains.

I'm uncomfortable with investigative reporting. It seems very wrong to me. Or, let me rephrase that - the article I'm writing and its consequences are not exactly something I'm comfortable with. Perhaps it's because I don't believe in it enough, or I can't really get the full feel for it. The angst behind it. The full-out passion towards it to question. I've grown up in a country where you don't ask questions. Really, you just don't. They shoot you for that shit. They put you in jail with all these internal security acts. I'm not used to this freedom of speech...not used to questioning out loud. Sure, I'm not the easiest person to get along with.

We ventured with colleagues to guintubdan and la carolota yesterday. It was our first time there. We trekked to the falls, a 30-minute walk. Breathless, we arrived at the water's edge. The cold water was invigorating, numbing our bodies. We stayed for less than an hour, but the scenery was breathtaking. The waterfalls were tranquil, and we felt one with nature. Immersing myself in the cold water was a rejuvenating experience, connecting with Mother Earth.

Some people are jumping to connect the dots : the Urllink organization for security and cooperation in Europe was invited to monitor the election by the State Department. Observers will come from the OSCE's Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights. It will be the first time such a team has been present for a US Presidential election. With Urllink, a baker's dozen of Congressional Democrats, including four New Yorkers, have petitioned UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan to dispatch international observers to Florida to oversee this year's presidential balloting there. I humbly disagree. Based on the information available, the OSCE seems to be coming here to learn from the US election process, not to oversee it, which was the original partisan and childish call for UN intervention.

GOP gets rebuked over recruitment at naturalization ceremonies in Jacksonville. New citizens were registered as Republicans without their knowledge or consent, sparking outrage. By Gary Fineout and Alfonso Chardy, the citizenship ceremony in Jacksonville seemed to go off as usual, with a crowd of nearly 200 people becoming new Americans. Just before the new citizens left, an immigration official directed them to stop by a voter registration table - a common sight at naturalization ceremonies. However, this table was unusual, as the volunteers handing out forms were Republican, and the party affiliation box had been checked off ahead of time, making all of the new voters members of the GOP without their knowledge or consent. Linda Cross was there to watch her husband, Dario Cruz, take his citizenship oath, and she was not pleased with the GOP's actions.

I found the idea of flag-burning as an offense to be intriguing, perhaps it could have been a way to escape being persecuted as a witch. As a non-American blogger, I've been hesitant to weigh in on these discussions, particularly those involving flags, but since I started writing about it (the subject, not the act of flag-burning), I suppose I should say something. Firstly, I believe that having a law against flag-burning is completely nonsensical. The moment you afford a symbol automatic reverence and protection, you're taking a small but significant step towards totalitarianism. Symbols are fleeting and their meanings are subjective - it's their interpretation that matters, not the symbol itself.

The given text is a legal document, specifically a memorandum, that notifies members of the New York Mercantile Exchange (NYMEX) and Comex of a new rule that has been approved by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC). The new rule, Rule 6.40c, relates to the calculation of average prices by futures commission merchants (FCMs) and is effective as of October 3, 2000.
The memo informs the recipients that the CFTC has approved the new rule, which allows FCMs to use their own internal, proprietary systems to generate average price ("AP") calculations when multiple prices are received on an order or series of orders. The new rule is attached to the memo and is now in effect.

I understand. In the old days, when we asked for resolutions evidencing the authority to enter into the master agreement/derivative transactions, we frequently received the resolutions without reviewing them thoroughly. Now that we are entering into a new era of energy trading, we want to make sure that we are aware of any potential risks and have a process in place to mitigate them.


To that end, I recommend that we review the resolutions contained in Lotus Notes and ensure that they are up-to-date and relevant to our current business needs. If there are any discrepancies or ambiguities in the resolutions, we should work with our legal and compliance teams to clarify them and ensure that they are consistent with our master agreement and other relevant agreements.
In addition, I suggest that we establish a process for regularly reviewing and updating the resolutions to ensure that they remain relevant and effective in the face of changing market conditions and regulatory requirements. By doing so, we can minimize the risk of errors or omissions in our transactions and ensure that we are operating in compliance with all relevant laws and regulations.

The spreadsheet shows the implicit commodity based on the effective date of four different rate schedules (Schedule DR) from August 2000 to September 2000, resulting in a larger commodity charge due to SD&E customers receiving a lump sum reimbursement from SD&E over those two months. As a result, SD&E customers can expect lower electric bills. Assuming the lump sum reimbursement is not included in the implicit energy component, the average for June 2000 through January 2001 is 6.2 cents, and the implicit commodity average from February 2001 through December 2001 is 7.3 cents. The average implicit commodity from June 2000 through December 2001 is 6.9 cents for deliveries starting September 1, 2000.

Sara Shackleton to Martin Rosell, forwarded by Sara Shackleton on 03/27/2001 10:27 am. Subject: Re: Commodity Futures Modernization Act. How are things going? In response to your question, there is no internal memo, but we do have copies of external law firm memoranda. Yes, Enron has changed its ISDA schedule form to provide for the 'eligible contract participant' rep and line of business. Magic fans beware: Wizards' digital game falls short. Despite being a social game at heart, you can't earn gold playing with friends. A daily cap on gold means it's a long and boring grind against the computer or random opponents. Even playing for free takes months to unlock cards.

Being the 3rd installment in the trilogy, I'll get the bad stuff out of the way first. I dislike pre-quarters as they go against the narrative flow and feel like a step backward in storytelling. While they provide additional story content, the combat feels clumsy and doesn't have the same sharpness as Arkham City's. As of October 23, 2013, there is a game-breaking bug that prevents a side mission from being completed (main story unaffected). Some gadgets are assigned to obscure keyboard hotkeys, making it difficult to access them during combat. While it may seem insignificant, this could potentially disrupt combos in the heat of the moment.

They basically fixed Shadow Warrior (2013). The boss fights are awesome, weapons feel very nice (though maybe not as good as D44m's), and enemies aren't too spongy (if you're not too bad at handling elemental and upgrade stuff). The upgrade system is well-balanced, and once you get the hang of it, it's not too tedious. The elemental stuff and limited ammo forces you to use different weapons. There are lots of cool unique weapons that stay viable throughout most of the game. The music is great, particularly the main theme, and of course, Stan Bush's contributions.

So many things went wrong. I can't even begin to start this review. This is all referred to my career. My player is an outside scorer, PG, 1.71m, and has maxed out all necessary perks. Okay, and now tell me, why does shooting skill depend on a person's height? Why can't someone with 1.74m become as skilled in shooting as someone with 1.71m? I'm 1.87m in real life and noticed that I couldn't reach a higher skill level than 89. Why? That's pure discrimination! And why doesn't the game tell me this before I create a character, or even after I reach the skill limit after weeks of playing?!

I see, it seems like you had a positive experience with the new collectible characters in the game! It's great to hear that they added some more interesting characters to the game and that you found them fun to collect. It's also good to know that they were not required to progress in the game, but they still had a purpose and were rewarding to collect. It's always nice when game developers listen to player feedback and make changes to improve the game. Do you have any favorite collectible characters in the game?

While the gameplay is decent, the pay-to-win model is a turn-off. The hardsuit is enjoyable, but I can't recommend it due to the monetization strategy. If you're okay with that, it's a fun game. Otherwise, it's not for me.

While not perfect, this game has been greatly enjoyable. The save system and possibility of sudden death leads to some frustration. I lost my main character around hour 10 of 20ish, and would have appreciated a save to reload at that point. I've since picked up a 3rd party mod/save tool to avoid catastrophic failures. The aiming reticule is on the small side, and the zoom is underpowered. Despite these issues, it's been a blast. I'm not normally a zombie fan, but the combination of strategy, missions, and first-person shooter/beat 'em up gameplay is great. I've been playing it as often as I can get away... Just one more mission, just one more supply run before I call it a night.

An absolute great strategy game! With a vast array of units and beautiful graphics, this game is a must-play for fans of the genre. The in-game chat at the main menu is also entertaining. However, be prepared to lose units and take your time to get the hang of it, especially if you're new to strategy games.

Ok, let's start on the pros and cons of this game. + Some of the best characters + good story + loads of content + customizable character (you can be male or female, whatever you like) + you can have a relationship with most of your companions (yes, fangirls, you can have a love interest) - bad graphics (I don't think graphics really matter anyway) - weird and awkward love scenes - invisible walls - their one mission in my opinion was boring, but everyone has different tastes - + um, this isn't really bad or good, but for those who care, your protagonist you made can't talk. Okay, I love this game. This game is probably one of the best RPGs or games in general I have ever played. So, if you're an RPG fan, you probably already have this game.

Yes, this game is a nostalgic delight for those who grew up with the original Transformers cartoon. Voice actors from the show return, and the cell-shaded graphics are perfect. The combat mechanics are well-done, with transforming in the middle of fights and melee combat a highlight. Despite some limitations, it's a fun game overall.

4k+ at 60fps (GTX 970), dual audio options, and includes Neptune gear. What's not to love? Excellent port and a great entry point for newcomers. Just keep in mind there's a lot of skip-able talking. As usual, suggest using a gamepad, but I had no issues with a keyboard/mouse setup. Price is right, and over half the DLC is included free. Recommended for all JRPG/anime/visual novel fans, but be prepared for long breaks between action. Cheers.

Thank you for sharing your experience! I'm glad to hear that the game runs smoothly on your system with the graphics settings set to "high." The game's graphics are indeed optimized for high-performance systems, but it's important to ensure that the game runs smoothly on a wide range of hardware configurations.



It's great to hear that the game is playable with an Xbox controller, as well. The game's developers have made sure to include support for a variety of input devices, including gamepads and joysticks, to ensure that players can enjoy the game with the control scheme that works best for them.
In terms of controls, the game can be played with keyboard and mouse, which are the default controls, but the game also supports gamepads and joysticks. This allows players to customize their control scheme to their preference, which can improve their gaming experience.
Overall, it seems that the game is well-optimized for high-performance systems, but it's also playable on a wide range of hardware configurations, including those with lower-end hardware.

You can see the hours I've put into this game by the enjoyment I've expressed. This is everything I wished a search game from COD would be. However, don't buy this game thinking it's like COD, Battlefield, or any other shooter game. It's a game in its own class and should be treated as such. Can't tell you how many times I've heard new players â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ and complain about getting killed quickly. Oh, god forbid you get shot in the face and â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ing die. It's not like that doesn't happen in real life or anything. I've been playing this game for a while now and thrown all kinds of money at it. One of the best MP games around. A good thing to play when you're not feeling CS:GO.

I'm 2 hours in and loving this game! The gameplay is solid, art design is beautiful, music is great, and the story/world is engaging. But the real highlight is the hilarious comedy. If you're an RPG fan, you'll love the parodies and references. Even if you're new to the genre, the humor will still make the game enjoyable. I had to stop playing after 2 hours to composed myself, my cheeks hurt from laughing. A true delight!

I apologize, but I didn't enjoy this game as much as I was hoping. Despite my interest in puzzle and exploration games, I found this game to be unintuitive and frustrating. The description initially piqued my interest, but the execution fell flat. I couldn't find the gameplay engaging, and even after looking up how to progress, I couldn't enjoy it. The lack of a pause button was particularly frustrating, as many sequences are timed, making it difficult to take breaks. Additionally, I felt like the game was more cutscenes than gameplay, leaving me feeling like I was just sitting around waiting for something to happen. Overall, I was disappointed with this game.

Wow, thank you so much for your kind words! We are thrilled to hear that you enjoyed playing as a playable character in our game and that you learned a lot about yourself through the experience. It's always rewarding to hear that our games can have a positive impact on players and help them understand themselves better.

We are also glad to hear that you were invested in the story and were eager to find out what happened next. Our goal is always to create immersive and engaging experiences for players, and it's great to hear that we were able to achieve that for you.

The positive feedback on the game's story and gameplay is much appreciated, and we're glad to hear that you would recommend it to everyone you know. We're always striving to improve and create better games, so your feedback is invaluable to us. Thank you again for playing and for taking the time to share your thoughts with us!

Sid Meier's Civilization: Beyond Earth is a turn-based game where you build your civilization to a goal or 'victory.' Unlike previous games, this one takes place in the future with new mechanics like the affinity system and orbital layer. While I appreciate the new additions, the game can be overwhelming at times. A potential improvement could be incorporating new artwork, such as the environments experienced during intergalactic communication.

Great game! Lots of replayability and a fun zombie survival experience. One of the better, more realistic zombie games I've played. Highly recommended with friends. PS: Get 1-2 friends to play with for a more enjoyable experience.

02/07/2014 - unfortunately, I cannot wholeheartedly recommend/enjoy this game due to two major issues. Firstly, the lack of Australian servers puts me at a significant disadvantage, causing unbearable lag. Even the offline training mode stutters and lags, which is baffling (how does that happen?). Secondly, everything artifacts terribly, including menus, backgrounds, training, and in-game elements. This has never happened before with this card, and I suspected it might not like my overclocking. Returning my GPU to stock settings made no difference.

Very late last night, I finished this. The story is not very deep or interesting, but what makes it stand out is the storytelling. The atmosphere is filled to the brim and the many collectibles do a great job at fleshing it out. I did learn a lot about the world of Batman, so it was a little disappointing that so few bosses were in the game. Oh well, there's enough future games to rectify that. The combat is the right amount of challenge, but it's more on the easy side. Leveling up Batman wasn't very satisfying. It's the gadgets you upgrade and acquire during the campaign that add nice new gameplay mechanics. Getting access to previously unreachable places makes for a nice sense of progression.

'To the moon' is no mere game... it's an unforgettable experience. One of the best of my life, with a storytelling pinnacle that surpasses even TellTale's The Walking Dead. The soundtrack is a perfect accompaniment, charming and depressingly fulfilling. The controls are finicky, but the story is so fantastic that I didn't care. Plus, the humor is great, never intruding upon the game's distinguished nature. Doctor Who references abound, adding to the game's charm.

I originally bought the game in its early stages when the only currency was Spacebux, and there was no 'tech tree.' This was when the game was good. All guns were equally overpowered, so there were no balance issues; everyone could kill anyone at any time. Additionally, the game provided unlimited gun slots and five loadouts. It's frustrating that for a game with 'bajillions of guns,' they only give you six weapon slots and three loadouts before you have to pay. At one point, I had around three pages of guns and was planning on coming up with new ideas, as I found it fun.

This game was a delightful surprise. Despite misleading reviews, it's a unique blend of 2D platformer and MOBA elements with a quirky charm. I was pleasantly surprised by the enjoyment I found in playing melee tank characters, which I wouldn't normally enjoy in other MOBA games. The art style and interface are charming, so I now use one of the characters as my avatar and created a card set based on the game.

I thoroughly enjoy this game. I put on my headphones and get completely immersed in it for hours on end. It's been a while since a game has had this kind of impact on me. The music sets the mood perfectly, and the sound effects are spot on. The controls are intuitive and responsive, and I look forward to every combat encounter. I was initially skeptical about the naval combat system, but it's surprisingly fun to unleash a barrage of attacks on multiple fleets at once. The only way to lose in this game is to fail to retreat. If the combat looks too overwhelming, just step back, regroup, and counter-attack. Thank you to the developers for creating such an enjoyable experience!

The reboot of the Devil May Cry franchise has brought about significant changes, particularly for the series' protagonist, Dante. While some fans may be displeased with the alterations to their beloved character, the new game by Ninja Theory demonstrates why these changes are for the better. DMC serves as an ideal entry point for newcomers to the series, showcasing the origins of an arrogant, cynical Dante and his transformation from cynicism to selflessness. The game's narrative arc effectively makes the new Dante a compelling character to watch, as he navigates a corrupt world he willfully ignored.

Where do I start on this delightful game? Its story is absolutely charming, filled with whimsy and humor. The attention to detail is impressive, with a rich tapestry of characters each with their own unique personalities and secrets. What sets it apart from other RPGs is its non-violent approach, a breath of fresh air in a genre often dominated by bloodshed. Inspired by Earthbound, one of the best RPGs I've seen, it's clear that this game has the potential to be something special. The soundtrack is equally impressive, with a soaring and uplifting score that will leave you smiling. Overall, this game has me excited for what's to come.

I recommend this game solely due to its free availability, despite my personal lack of engagement. The game's reliance on shock value was not effective in eliciting a response from me. The other half of the game, which explores themes of obsession, hallucination, and depression, shows promise in its concept. However, the brevity of the game (10 minutes) and lack of depth in its execution left me unmoved.

If you can overlook the minor bug, I can definitely recommend this game. Since most reviews focus on specs, I'll share my setup: i5 6600k (~200â‚¬), Radeon RX480 (~200â‚¬), Z170 Pro - Gaming (~150â‚¬), 16GB DDR4 RAM (~70â‚¬). My rig provides almost constant 60+ fps with vsync enabled, despite being within the medium price range. I can't believe 90% of the comments claiming they have an overkill setup and only get 20fps.

I completely agree with you! Divinity: Dragon Commander is a fantastic game that offers a unique blend of real-time strategy and fantasy elements. The ability to play as a dragon and command your troops from the skies is incredibly immersive and adds a new layer of depth to the gameplay. The risk-like grand strategy aspect of the game also adds an extra layer of challenge and replayability, as you have to carefully manage your resources and make strategic decisions to ensure your faction's success.

I too have found that I prefer more complex RTS games like Civilization V and the like, where the gameplay is more slow-paced and there is more depth to the game mechanics. However, I do appreciate the challenge and depth that these types of games offer, and I think they are great for players who enjoy a more strategic and thoughtful gameplay experience.

Based on the review, the game is a casual game that offers repetitive gameplay with frequent updates and new content. The reviewer mentions that the game is free, so it's worth trying out, but it may not hold the player's attention for a long time due to its repetitive nature. However, the updates and new content added to the game may provide a fresh experience and keep the gameplay interesting. Overall, the review suggests that the game is suitable for casual players who enjoy grinding and don't mind repetitive gameplay.

3. The levels are not "inventive." They are designed to be surreal and thought-provoking, with a focus on exploration and puzzle-solving.
4. The game is not a "horror show." While there are some dark and unsettling elements, the game is not intended to be a horror game.
5. The creators of the game do not have an "interest in taxidermy." This is a common misconception, as the game's creator, Simon Cheng, is an independent game developer who has no interest in tax

"Oh, wow, it's not that bad! I mean, it's not like I was expecting a revolutionary game or anything, but I was hoping for a bit more depth to it. I mean, it's just a simple game where you pick a side and play as that side's candidate, but I was hoping for something more. I guess the character customization is the highlight of the game, but even that's not that great. It's just a few options, and you can't customize your character's appearance or anything like that. I was really looking forward to it, but it's just a letdown. Oh well, I'll give it a shot, might as well play it for a bit and see where it goes. Maybe it'll get better as you get further in. But for now, it's just not that great.

Fallout 4's story was better than its predecessor, but settlements can be a hindrance. Some keys are hard-coded and cannot be rebound. Bugs and glitches were present, including a permanent disappearance of my pipboy. Power armor is readily available, but its value has diminished from previous games. While more stable than Fallout 3, the story is unremarkable. Not better than New Vegas, in my opinion.

I spent 8.6 hours completing this game, finding 10 collectibles out of 25, and completing zero achievements. The visuals were good until the final level, but the last level's visuals were uninteresting and the gameplay became frustrating as it required repetition to get it right. Only 13% of players have achieved all 15 achievements.

Pros: +Graphics Cons: -Bugs (especially in the environment, leading to frustrating moments where shots miss invisible walls or you get stuck) -Game can feel too handholding/babysitting -Dumb AI -Enemies have uncanny accuracy -Terrible checkpoints and saves -Boring story that lacks engagement -Won't recommend unless heavily discounted, even then, it's a chore to play.

Review for 29/11/2015: Don't buy this game, servers offline. Can't play. While I could play it, I enjoyed it. As the Steve Miller Band song goes: 'Go on, take the money and run.' Some guns are OP, matchmaking can be unfair, but hey, BF3's matchmaking is worse. Newbies face real humans, but nothing happens when shot.

The World Economic Forum (WEF) is holding its annual meeting in Davos, Switzerland, which is a gathering of world leaders and experts from various fields to discuss global issues and shape the global agenda. The meeting is taking place from January 22 to 25, and it is expected to be attended by more than 3,000 people, including government leaders, business executives, academics, and civil society representatives.
The UK Prime Minister, Tony Blair, and the President of South Africa, Thabo Mbeki, are among the more than 20 government leaders and heads of state attending the meeting. Unlike previous years, protests against the WEF are expected to be muted. Anti-globalization campaigners have called off a demonstration planned for the weekend. The Brazilian city of Porto Alegre will host the rival World Social Forum, timed to run in parallel with the WEF's more glamorous event in Davos.

The Catholic Church's stance on the Iraq War
Cardinal Cormac Murphy-O'Connor has spoken out against the Iraq War, calling it a "terrible" waste of money that could have been used to reduce poverty and improve living conditions in the Middle East. In a Christmas message, he criticized the fact that "billions" of pounds have been spent on the conflict, instead of being used to address the needs of the poor and marginalized. The cardinal, who is the head of the Catholic Church in England and Wales, urged people to make 2005 a year of campaigning to "make history" and end poverty.
The cardinal's comments come at a time when the war in Iraq is entering its fourth year, with no clear end in sight. The conflict has caused widespread destruction and loss of life, and has been widely criticized for its impact on the people of Iraq and the wider region.
Cardinal Murphy-O'Connor's call for action on poverty is a reminder that the war in Iraq is not only a political and military conflict, but also a humanitarian crisis with far-reaching consequences. It is a reminder that the world's resources are being used to fund weapons and military action, rather than to address the basic needs of the world's poorest and most vulnerable people.

Halloween screenwriter and producer Debra Hill, best known for her work on the 1978 horror classic Halloween, has died in Los Angeles at the age of 54. Hill, who had been suffering from cancer, co-wrote the film, which starred Jamie Lee Curtis as a babysitter terrorized by a psychopath. Directed by John Carpenter, it grossed over $60 million worldwide, a record for an independent film at the time. Hill also worked with Carpenter on Escape from New York and The Fog. Hill, who was born in New Jersey, began her career as a production assistant and worked her way up to become an assistant director and second-unit director before collaborating with Carpenter. She was a pioneering woman in the film industry, taking on jobs in the 1970s that were typically held by men.

Yukos, a US-based oil and gas company, is facing a legal battle in a US court as it fights to save its survival. The company is in the process of being broken up by Russian authorities in order to pay a $27bn (Â£14bn) tax bill. Yukos had filed for bankruptcy in the US, hoping to use international business law to halt the forced sale of its key oil production unit, Yuganskneftegas. However, the unit was sold for $9.4bn to state oil firm Rosneft, but only after the state auction had been disrupted. Yukos' lawyers now say that the auction violated US bankruptcy law. The company and its main shareholders have vowed to go after any company that buys its assets, using all and every legal means.

Voters flock to blog awards site for annual bloggies, voting for the best web blogs - online spaces where people publish their thoughts. Nominations were announced on Sunday, but website traffic was so heavy that it was temporarily closed due to too many visitors. Blogs have been nominated in 30 categories, from top regional blog to best-kept-secret blog. Blogs had a big year, with a top US dictionary naming "blog" word of 2004. Technorati, a blog search engine, tracks over six million blogs and says that more than 12,000 are added daily. A new blog is created every 5.8 seconds, according to US research think-tank Pew Internet and American Life, but less than 40% of them are updated at least once every two months.

Chinese dam builder defies Beijing, continues work on controversial dam despite government order to halt construction. China Three Gorges Project Corp. is ignoring the order for its Xiluodu Dam, one of 30 large-scale projects targeted for environmental violations. The company may face a fine instead of halting work.

Manchester United reduced Chelsea's Premier League lead to nine points after a scrappy victory over Manchester City. Wayne Rooney met Gary Neville's cross to the near post with a low shot, which went in via a deflection off Richard Dunne to put United ahead. Seven minutes later, the unfortunate Dunne hooked a volley over David James' head and into his own net. Steve McManaman wasted City's best chance when he shot wide from three yards in the first half. In the opening 45 minutes, United had looked unlikely to earn the win they needed to keep their title hopes alive, their approach play was more labored than patient and they managed to fashion just one chance - a Paul Scholes header over the bar.

Ferguson praises Man Utd's gutsy win at Aston Villa.

Alex Ferguson hailed Manchester United's gutsy performance in their 1-0 win at Aston Villa, describing it as their hardest away game of the season. The Old Trafford boss praised his players' determination and character, saying they showed plenty of both to secure the victory. "It was an end-to-end game with lots of good passing, and we showed great character and guts to win," Ferguson said. "We weren't going to lose, and I think we've set the tone for the rest of the season." Ferguson also singled out senior stars Ryan Giggs and Roy Keane, who came off the bench for the injured John O'Shea, saying they provided the composure and leadership the team needed.

George Michael to be profiled at Berlin Film Festival
Michael will introduce screening of documentary at festivalGeorge Michael will be profiled at this year's Berlin Film Festival, where a documentary about his life and career will be screened. The film, titled "George Michael: Freedom, Love, and Life," will have its world premiere at the festival on February 16 and will be shown in the Panorama section of the festival, which runs from February 10-20. The documentary, which is 93 minutes long, will give an in-depth look at Michael's life, from his early days in Wham! to his more recent career and personal struggles. Michael will attend the festival to introduce the screening on February 16.Director Southan Morris and executive producer Andy Stephens will also attend the festival. The documentary will feature Michael discussing his early days in Wham!, as well as his later career, including his legal battles with record label Sony and his stance against the Iraq war and American politics.

Green Day's "Boulevard of Broken Dreams" is currently at number two on Billboard's Hot 100 chart, and tops its digital chart. Download sales are expected to be incorporated into the UK singles chart later this year. Digital sales in the US are already used to compile Billboard's Hot Digital Sales chart. They will now be tallied with sales of physical singles and airplay information to make up its new Hot 100 chart. Its second new chart, the Pop 100, combines airplay, digital and physical sales, but confines its airplay information to US radio stations that play chart music.

Anti-spam laws have bitten the self-proclaimed spam king, OptinRealBig, hard, as the company has filed for bankruptcy protection. Scott Richter, the mastermind behind the operation, has been embroiled in several legal battles, including a high-profile lawsuit with Microsoft, which is seeking millions of dollars in damages. The company, listed as the third biggest spammer in the world by junk mail watchdog SpamHaus, was sued in December 2003 for sending mail messages that violated anti-spam laws. The lawsuit was brought by Microsoft and New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, who alleged that Richter and his accomplices sent billions of spam messages through 514 compromised net addresses in 35 countries.

Ireland surged past Scotland in their Six Nations match at Murrayfield, securing an impressive victory and maintaining their grand slam ambitions. Hugo Southwell's try gave the Scots an early 8-0 lead, but scores from locks Malcolm O'Kelly and Paul O'Connell put the visitors in command by half-time. A third try from wing Denis Hickie and third penalty from Ronan O'Gara, who kicked 13 points, extended the lead. Jon Petrie scored a second try for Scotland, but late scores from John Hayes and Gavin Duffy sealed the victory. After two hard-earned away victories, Eddie O'Sullivan's side can now look forward to welcoming England to Lansdowne Road in a fortnight. Scotland will aim to give their coach Matt Williams a first Six Nations victory when Italy come to Edinburgh, but they again struggled to turn pressure into points.

Brizzel to defend 200m title in Sheffield AAA Championships. Eight Irish athletes, including Brizzel and McIlroy, will compete. Cragg and Carroll are selected for Europeans but will not run in Sheffield. Brizzel and McIlroy in form, with Brizzel defending his title and McIlroy hoping to confirm place in British team for Madrid.

Iraq Invites Bids for Phone License, Seeks to Boost Nationwide Coverage

Iraq's Ministry of Communications has invited bids from local, Arab, and foreign companies to develop and operate a fixed phone network, with the aim of significantly increasing the country's telephone service penetration rate. The ministry is seeking to boost coverage from the current 4.5% to around 25% within the next decade.

The winning bidder will partner with the Iraqi Telecommunications and Post Company (ITPC) to install and operate a fixed phone network, providing voice, fax, and internet services. The ministry hopes to establish a highly visible and dynamic telecommunications sector, with the goal of improving communication services across the country.

The bidding and tender process will be published on the ministry's website on February 9, and a roadshow for investors in Amman, Jordan is also planned. Interested companies are invited to submit their bids by the deadline of March 16.

More women are taking charge of protecting their home computers against malicious net attacks, according to a two-year study by a net security firm. The number of women buying programs to protect PCs from viruses, spam, and spyware rose by 11.2% each year between 2002 and 2004. The study, which surveyed 1,000 net users, shows that 40% of those buying home net security software are retired. This is up from an average of 13.2% for the past three years. The research also found that more retired women (53%) are buying security software than retired men. The findings reflect changing stereotypes and demographics of web users, as well as growing awareness of the greater risks that high-speed broadband connections pose to surfers.

Podcasts have emerged as a popular medium for audio content creation, allowing individuals to produce and distribute their own radio-like shows through the internet. The term "podcasting" is derived from the Apple iPod, although it is not necessary to use an iPod to create or listen to a podcast. Podcasters create and upload their shows to the internet for others to download and listen to, free of charge. This has led to a proliferation of audio content created by an unpredictable array of producers. Adam Curry, a former MTV host and VJ (video jockey), is a prominent proponent of podcasting. Podcasting is essentially an internet-based radio show that podcasters create in the comfort of their own homes, using only a microphone, a computer, and some editing software.

Andrea Levy's novel Small Island has won the Whitbread Novel of the Year award, making her the favorite to win the overall prize. She is joined by Geraldine McCaughrean, who won the Children's Fiction award for the third time. The winners of all categories will compete for the Book of the Year title, which comes with a Â£25,000 prize. A panel of judges, including Sir Trevor McDonald, Hugh Grant, and Joanne Harris, will announce the winner on January 25. Bookmaker William Hill has placed Levy's novel as the 6/4 favorite to win.

Yukos will return to court on Wednesday to seek sanctions against Baikal Finance Group, the little-known firm that bought its main asset. Yukos will sue Baikal and others involved in the sale of Yuganskneftegas for $20 billion in damages. Yukos' US lawyers will attempt to have Baikal's assets frozen after the Russian government ignored a US court order last week blocking the sale. The background and Baikal's motives for buying the Yuganskneftegas production unit are still unclear. Russian newspapers have claimed that Baikal, which bought the unit for $9.4 billion (261 billion roubles, Â£4.8 billion) on Sunday at a state-provoked auction, has strong links with Surgutneft, Russia's fourth-largest oil producer.

Hearts wrapped up their Scottish Cup quarter-final tie against Livingston with two goals in the first 10 minutes. Lee Miller scored inside the opening 60 seconds, heading over Colin Meldrum and into the net from a Jamie McAllister free kick. McAllister himself scored the second when he met Saul Mikoliunas' cross at the back post to put the game beyond the visitors. With just 10 minutes on the clock, the home side doubled their lead. Mikoliunas sprinted down the right and crossed to the back post, where McAllister raced in to head past Meldrum.

Sun Microsystems, a leading provider of computing and software solutions, has announced the launch of its Grid Computing service, a new computing model that allows customers to rent computing power on demand. The Sun Grid is a utility-based computing service that provides customers with on-demand access to computing resources, such as processing power, storage, and applications, over the internet.
 Sun believes that Grid Computing is the future of computing, and that computing capacity will become as important as hardware and software.
"Why build your own grid when you can use ours for a buck an hour?" said Jonathan Schwartz, Sun's chief operating officer, in a webcast launching Sun's quarterly Network Computing event in California. "Grid computing is the next step in the evolution of computing, just like electricity and water. It's a utility, not a product."

Sun's Grid Computing service is designed to provide customers with a flexible and cost-effective way to access computing resources on an as-needed basis. Customers can rent computing power, storage, and applications from Sun's data centers, located in various locations around the world, and use them as needed. The service is ideal for customers who have variable computing needs, such as scientific research, financial modeling, and data analysis, which can be spiky and unpredictable.

Sun's Grid Computing

Scotland's Justice Minister, Cathy Jamieson, has issued a warning to bigoted soccer fans, threatening to ban them from matches if they do not change their behavior. Jamieson stated that she wants to hit them "where it hurts most" by banning them from games. She praised Celtic and Rangers for their efforts in tackling the problem of sectarianism, but emphasized that stopping sectarian abuse associated with Old Firm matches is a key objective. The minister was speaking ahead of the third round of the Scottish Cup clash between the Glasgow clubs at Parkhead on Sunday. Sectarianism has long been a significant problem in Scottish football, with sections of the support from both clubs often being associated with sectarian chanting and behavior. The Scottish Executive has made addressing the issue a priority, and Jamieson's comments suggest that action may be taken against fans who fail to comply with the rules. Last week, Jamieson and First Minister Jack McConnell met with representatives from both clubs to discuss the issue.

Leeds v Saracens (Friday, February 25th, 2000 GMT) - The Tykes have brought in new recruits from the borders on loan, with Fly-half Craig McMullen joining from Narbonne, while prop Kalman and Tom McGee are also on their way from the borders. Raphael Ibanez is named at Hooker for Saracens in one of four changes. Simon Raiwalui and Ben Russell are also selected in the pack, while Kevin Sorrell comes in at Outside Centre. Replacements: Kalman, Regan, Hyde, McMillan, Rock, Vickerman.

Scott was slightly disappointed with his run in the final. He won his heat in 7.64secs but ran 0.04secs slower in his first IAAF indoor grand prix final.

IRB Rugby Aid Match: Ireland's Brian O'Driscoll, France's Fabien Pelous, Scotland's Gordon Bullock, and Italy's Marco Bortolami are part of the Northern Hemisphere squad for the IRB Rugby Aid match on March 5. Sir Clive Woodward will coach the Northern Hemisphere team against Rod MacQueen's Southern Hemisphere team in a Tsumani fund-raising match at Twickenham. "I'm looking forward to working with such outstanding players," he said. It will be a chance for Woodward to assess some of his options before unveiling his British and Irish Lions touring party, who will visit New Zealand in the summer. "The game promises to be a great spectacle," he said.

Sideways dominated this year's Independent Spirit Awards, taking home all six awards it was nominated for, including Best Film, Best Director, and Best Screenplay for Alexander Payne and writing partner Jim Taylor. The film also won acting awards for Paul Giamatti, Thomas Haden Church, and Virginia Madsen. With five nominations, Sideways is tipped to do well at Sunday's Oscars. The Independent Spirit Awards, now in their 20th year, recognize films made outside the traditional studio system. Other winners included Catalina Sandino Moreno, who took home Best Actress for her role as a drug smuggler in the Colombian drama Maria Full of Grace. Moreno is also nominated for Best Actress at the Oscars. The Best First Screenplay award went to Joshua Marston for Maria Full of Grace.

Prince was crowned the "top music earner" in 2004, outranking Madonna and Elton John in US Magazine's Rolling Stone list. He earned $56.5 million (Â£30.4 million) from concerts, album, and publishing sales with his Musicology tour and album. Prince kept Madonna in second place, as she earned $54.9 million (Â£29.5 million) during her global re-invention tour. Veterans Simon and Garfunkel were in 10th place, their comeback tour contributing $24.9 million (Â£13.4 million) last year. Prince returned to center stage after a decade in the commercial wilderness, according to the magazine. His 2004 tour generated $90.3 million (Â£48.5 million) in ticket sales, and he sold 1.9 million copies of his latest album, Musicology.

1. The Conservatives have unveiled plans to give local communities the opportunity to elect their own police commissioner through a poll.
2. The new role would replace the "inconspicuous" police authorities and would not supersede the job of a chief constable.
3. The Liberal Democrats believe the plan could allow extreme groups to take control of policing.
4. Labour has criticized the Conservatives for making "extravagant" promises on policing.
5. The chairman of the Police Federation of England and Wales warned that it is essential to retain operational independence.
6. Jan Berry said the plans could result in those with extreme political views dictating what happens on the ground.

Paris, France - Saturday's epic rugby match between Wales and France has left fans and pundits alike in awe. The Welsh team's stunning victory has raised hopes of a grand slam, the first since 1978, and has been hailed as one of the greatest performances in recent years. Welsh legend Mervyn Davies, a member of two Grand Slam-winning sides of the 1970s, described it as "one of the most surreal games I have ever seen." Wales' two-try scorer, Martyn Williams, called it "one of the most surreal games I have ever played in." French coach Bernard Laporte simply observed, "There was a French half, and there was a Welsh half." The match has sparked a renewed sense of optimism in Welsh rugby, and fans are eagerly anticipating the team's next match.

Doves soar to UK album summit with new release. Manchester rock band Doves have reached number one on the UK album chart with their latest release, "Some Cities." They replace US act Scissor Sisters at the top of the chart. R&B star Nelly has the number one single with "Over and Over," a collaboration with Tim McGraw. Girls Aloud, Akon, and Kaiser Chiefs also have new singles in the top ten. Elvis Presley's latest re-release, "Marie's the Name," enters the chart at number three, just ahead of Girls Aloud's "Wake Me Up." Akon's "Locked Up" is at number five, while hotly-tipped Leeds band Kaiser Chiefs have their second chart hit at number six with "Oh My God.

Davies favours Gloucester future, Wales hooker unlikely to leave despite Ospreys interest. BBC Wales understands the Ospreys are interested in the 32-year-old, but he would prefer to stay with Gloucester. Davies, a star of Saturday's RBS Six Nations win over England, is only on a one-year contract at Kingsholm, but he has proven his worth to the Zurich Premiership side and is likely to get a new deal next season. The summer demise of the Celtic Warriors region left Davies in the cold and forced him to take a semi-professional contract with Neath RFC. Although he got match time with the Ospreys at the request of Welsh management, he admitted before his move to Gloucester that he was angry with the way he was treated.

The UK government has announced a Â£1 billion package to help local authorities in England keep council tax rises below 5%, in what is likely to be a general election year. The package includes Â£200 million in additional funding for local authorities to help them deliver good services without large council tax rises. The central government cash is part of a Â£1 billion package to help local authorities in England keep next year's council tax rises below 5%, in what is likely to be a general election year.
 Mr Raynsford said nearly all central government departments had an interest in well-run local authorities.

Israeli club HaPoel Bnei Sakhnin look to Africa for four African players, including Zimbabwean goalkeeper Energy Murambadoro, to play in the Uefa Cup. Bnei Sakhnin, the first Arab side to play in European competition, will face English Premiership side Newcastle United in the first round. Murambadoro, who impressed at the African Nations Cup finals in Tunisia, helped Bnei Sakhnin overcome Albania's Partizani Tirana 6-1 in the previous round. The club, based in Sakhnin near Haifa, have a strong ethos and promote peace and cooperation within Israel.

New drink-drive limit 'could save 65 lives a year': A report from University College London claims that cutting the drink-drive limit from 80mg of alcohol per 100ml of blood to 50mg could save 65 lives annually. The findings are being published as MPs prepare to vote on the government's road safety bill, which includes changes to speeding fines but not the drink-drive limit. According to transport expert Professor Richard Allsop, the change would also lead to 230 fewer serious injuries on the UK's roads, saving the country Â£119m per year.

This paper presents a millimeter-scale CMOS 64$\times$64 single charged particle radiation detector system for external beam cancer radiotherapy. A 1$\times$1 $\mu m^2$ diode measures energy deposition by a single charged particle in the depletion region, providing a large detection area of 512$\times$512 $\mu m^2$. Instead of sensing the voltage drop caused by radiation, the proposed system measures the pulse width, i.e., the time it takes for the voltage to return to its baseline. This approach eliminates the need for power-hungry and large analog-to-digital converters. A prototype ASIC was fabricated in TSMC 65 nm LP CMOS process and consumes an average static power of 0.535 mW under 1.2 V analog and digital power supply. The functionality of the whole system was successfully verified in a clinical 67.5 MeV proton beam setting."

The text discusses the potential of optomechanics and electromechanics to create macroscopic mechanical oscillators in their quantum ground states, squeezed states, and entangled states of motion. The ability to manipulate and control these oscillators has the potential to revolutionize the processing and communication of quantum information and precision force sensing beyond the standard quantum limit. However, the linear interaction between motion and light or electricity hinders access to a broader class of quantum states, such as cat states or energy-squeezed states. Early optomechanical proposals suggested the possibility of strong quadratic coupling of motion to light to escape this restriction. Although there have been experimental demonstrations of quadratically coupled optomechanical systems, these have not yet accessed non-classical states of motion.

Online reviews provide customers with product evaluations, but they can be manipulated by spammers using increasingly sophisticated spamming strategies. These strategies are difficult to detect due to their variability, adaptability, and unknown nature. Most detectors focus on accuracy, but this approach can undermine the trustworthiness of product evaluations. To address these challenges, we formulate a game-theoretic approach that pits spammers and detectors against each other, with the goal of achieving a stable equilibrium that balances detection accuracy and trustworthiness.

We developed single-shot shaped pulses for ultra-high fidelity (uh-fidelity) population transfer on a 3-level quantum system in lambda configuration. Using the Lewis-Riesenfeld (L-R) method, we derived a family of solutions leading to exact transfer, with solutions following a single dynamical mode of the L-R invariant. Among this family, we identified a tracking solution with a single parameter to control fidelity, population, and robustness. We defined a measure of robustness as the minimum percentile deviation in pulse areas where infidelity rises above $10^{-4}$. Our shaped pulses showed superior robustness compared to Gaussian and adiabatically optimized pulses for moderate pulse areas.

In this paper, we investigate the landscape of the population negative log-likelihood function of Gaussian mixture models with an arbitrary number of components. Due to nonconvexity, there exist multiple local minima that are not globally optimal, even when the mixture is well-separated. We show that all local minima share the same form of structure, which involves fitting a non-overlapping combination of Gaussians to a single true component and fitting a single Gaussian to multiple true components. Our results hold for the setting where the true mixture components satisfy a certain separation condition and are valid for both over- and under-specified models. For Gaussian mixtures with three components, we obtain sharper results in terms of the scaling with the separation between the components.

We investigate the connection between two constructions of the mirror partner for a Calabi-Yau orbifold. The orbifold is defined as a quotient by a suitable subgroup $g$ of the phase symmetries of the hypersurface $x_m$ in a weighted projective space, cut out by a quasi-homogeneous polynomial $w_m$. The first construction, Berglund-H\"ubsch-Krawitz (BHK), uses another weighted projective space and the quotient of a new hypersurface $x_{m^t}$ inside it by some dual group $g^t$. In the second construction, Batyrev, the mirror partner is constructed as a hypersurface in the toric variety defined by the reflexive polytope dual to the polytope associated with the original Calabi-Yau orbifold. We provide a simple evidence of the equivalence of these two constructions.

We present a new mixed variable symplectic (mvs) integrator for planetary systems, fully resolving close encounters. The method combines time regularization and a high-order scheme to maintain stability and accuracy far from encounters, while reducing the effective step size during close approaches. We demonstrate the algorithm's ability to resolve almost exact collisions while using the same time step as in weakly perturbed problems, such as the solar system. Long-term behavior is shown on systems of six super-Earths experiencing strong scattering over 50 kyr, with comparisons to hybrid methods like Mercury.

Entanglement is a crucial resource for quantum information processing. A widely used tool for detecting entanglement is entanglement witness, which measures the witness operator and guarantees a positive value for separable states and a negative value for certain entangled states. However, as the number of parties increases, it becomes increasingly difficult to construct an efficient entanglement witness for general multipartite entangled states. For $n$-partite Greenberger-Horne-Zeilinger (GHZ)-like states, the most robust witness scheme requires $n+1$ local measurement settings and can tolerate up to $1/2$ white noise. In contrast, the most efficient witness for GHZ-like states requires only two local measurement settings and can tolerate up to $1/3$ white noise.

In general relativity, the unique stationary solution is the Kerr spacetime with a multipolar structure depending on mass and spin. We develop a method to extract multipole moments from arbitrary stationary spacetimes and apply it to a large family of horizonless microstate geometries. These geometries can break the axial and equatorial symmetry of the Kerr metric, leading to a richer multipolar structure that provides a portal to constrain fuzzball models phenomenologically. Numerical evidence suggests that multipole moments are typically larger than those of a Kerr black hole with the same mass and spin.

In this paper, the authors propose a new approach to address the limitations of traditional graph neural networks (GNNs) in social network analysis, which are often criticized for their reliance on human-specified edges. Traditional GNNs rely on explicit edge information, which can be time-consuming and suboptimal to obtain, especially for large-scale networks. The proposed method, called Temporal Point Processes and Variational Autoencoders for Inferring Temporal Attention in Graphs (TPP-VAE), leverages temporal point processes and variational autoencoders to learn the dynamics of node interactions and infer temporal attention between nodes. The key idea is to observe the temporal interactions between nodes and use the resulting dynamics to learn the attention patterns between them.
The authors evaluate their approach on several real-world social networks and demonstrate its effectiveness in capturing subtle patterns in the data that are not captured by traditional GNNs. They show that TPP-VAE outperforms state-of-the-art GNNs in terms of both accuracy and computational efficiency, and provides a more flexible and interpretable way of modeling temporal attention in social networks.

Observations of thermally driven transverse vibration of a photonic crystal waveguide (pcw) are reported. The pcw consists of two parallel nanobeams with a 240 nm vacuum gap between the beams. Models are developed and validated for transducing beam motion into phase and amplitude modulation of a weak optical probe propagating in a guided mode (gm) of the pcw for probe frequencies near and far from the dielectric band edge. This research provides a foundation for evaluating possible deleterious effects of thermal motion on optical atomic traps near the surfaces of pcws, with longer-term goals of achieving strong atom-mediated links between individual phonons of vibration and single photons in the gms of the pcw, enabling opto-mechanics at the quantum level with atoms, photons, and phonons.

The statement you are referring to is a fundamental result in algebraic topology, and it is indeed a consequence of the splitting of the homotopy groups of spheres into a direct sum of copies of the fundamental group of the circle.


The result you are referring to is the Mayer-Vietoris-Bott theorem, which states that for any closed, oriented, and connected manifold $M$, there exists a long exact sequence of the form
$$\to \pi_0(M) \to \pi_1(M) \to \pi_2(M) \to \cdots \to \pi_n(M)$$

where each of the maps in the sequence is a homotopy map, and the kernel of the map $\pi_n(M) \to \pi_n(M)$ is a free abelian group of rank $n$.

In particular, if $M$ is a sphere, then the long exact sequence splits, and we have a short exact sequence of the form
$$\to \pi_0(M) \to \pi_1(M) \to \pi_2(M) \to \pi_2(M) \to \pi_3(M)$$

where $\pi_2(M)$ is a free abelian group

Baryonic feedback effects lead to a suppression of the weak lensing angular power spectrum on small scales. The poorly constrained shape and amplitude of this suppression is an important source of uncertainties for upcoming cosmological weak lensing surveys, such as Euclid or LSST. In this first paper in a series of two, we use simulations to build a Euclid-like tomographic mock data set for the cosmic shear power spectrum and the corresponding covariance matrix, which are both corrected for baryonic effects following the baryonification method of Schneider et al. (2019). In addition, we develop an emulator to obtain fast predictions of the baryonic power suppression, allowing us to perform a likelihood inference analysis for a standard Î›CDM cosmology with both cosmological and astrophysical parameters.

The authors of this paper propose an open-source neural network approach to classify audio segments into three categories: vocalizations produced by the child wearing the recording device, vocalizations produced by other children, and adult male and female speech. They aim to address the challenge of processing speech in real-world settings, where children's speech is often mixed with other sounds, such as background noise or the speech of other children.
The authors gathered a diverse corpus of child-centered speech recordings, which sums up to a total of 260 hours of recordings and covers 10 languages. They use this corpus to train and evaluate their neural network model, which they propose as a novel approach to speech processing in child-centered settings. The proposed model can be used for a variety of applications, including language acquisition research, early diagnosis of speech and language disorders, and developing personalized interventions for language learning.
The proposed approach is based on a convolutional neural network (CNN) architecture, which is well-suited for processing sequential data such as speech. The CNN is trained on a large dataset of audio segments, each labeled with one of the three categories mentioned above.
