The paper "Modal Clustering: A Nonparametric Approach to Density-based Clustering" by Zhang and Zhang (2009) proposes a nonparametric approach to density-based clustering, called modal clustering. The authors aim to address the issue of density estimation for modal clustering, which is a fundamental problem in clustering analysis, as traditional methods for density estimation, such as k-means, are not directly applicable to modal clustering.
The authors define modal clustering as the partition of the data into groups, where each group is characterized by a density mode, which is a point in the data space where the density of the data is maximized. The density modes are obtained by minimizing the Kullback-Leibler divergence between the true density of the data and a probability distribution, which is used as an approximation to the true density.The proposed method, called modal clustering, consists of two main steps: (1) density estimation, and (2) clustering. In the first step, the authors use a nonparametric density estimate, such as a kernel density estimate, to obtain an estimate of the true density of the data. In the second step, the authors apply a clustering algorithm, such as k-means or hierarchical clustering

The tails of diboson production at the LHC are sensitive to the interference between standard model and higher-dimensional operators, which parameterize the effects of heavy new physics. However, helicity selection rules for the diboson scattering amplitudes impose an obstruction to the naive interference contributions of dimension six operators, suppressing the leading contribution to the total diboson rate correction. In this case, measuring the azimuthal decay angles "resurrects" the interference, allowing for sensitivity to the "non-interfering" operators. We explore these signatures in detail, and find that the EFT uncertainties associated with higher-dimensional operators are uniquely well-suppressed by the construction of an asymmetry variable that is generated only by these non-interfering operators, relegating the effects of higher-dimensional, interfering operators to the same status as statistical errors in this observable.

The argument you are referring to is indeed a famous result in the field of quantum gravity and black hole physics, known as the "Waldinger-Hawking no-go theorem". It states that it is impossible to consistently combine the principles of general relativity and quantum mechanics in a theory of quantum gravity, at least in the sense of producing a unitary and causal theory.

The proof of this theorem is based on the idea that the entanglement entropy of a black hole, which is a measure of the quantum information contained in the black hole, is not a local quantity, but rather a non-local one. Specifically, it is proportional to the area of the event horizon of the black hole, and its value cannot be determined by local measurements within the black hole.
This means that any local theory of quantum gravity that attempts to describe the black hole must either be inconsistent with the principles of general relativity, or it must introduce non-local degrees of freedom, which are not present in classical general relativity.
The no-go theorem has been a major challenge in the development of a consistent theory of quantum gravity, as it seems to rule out many promising approaches to the problem. However, it has also led to the development of new ideas and approaches, such as loop quantum gravity and string theory, which attempt to avoid the contradiction by introducing new degrees of freedom and non-locality.

Understanding how strongly correlated two-dimensional (2D) systems can exhibit unconventional superconductivity at high critical temperatures is a major unsolved problem in condensed matter physics. Ultracold 2D fermi gases have emerged as clean and controllable model systems to study the interplay of strong correlations and reduced dimensionality, but direct evidence of superfluidity in these systems has been lacking. We demonstrate superfluidity in an ultracold 2D fermi gas by moving a periodic potential through the system and observing no dissipation below a critical velocity, v$_{\rm c}$. We measure v$_{\rm c}$ as a function of interaction strength and find a maximum in the crossover regime between bosonic and fermionic superfluidity. Our measurement establishes ultracold fermi gases as a powerful tool for studying the influence of reduced dimensionality on strongly correlated superfluids.

The paper "Spin polarization of cooper pairs in a chiral junction" by Weyl nodes" by numerical simulations" by X.Y.Zhang, et al. (2017) presents a study on the spin polarization of cooper pairs in a chiral junction using numerical simulations. The authors consider a two-dimensional model with a chiral junction and use the Weyl node approach to calculate the differential conductance and pairing amplitudes. They find that the spin polarization of cooper pairs is strongly dependent on the angle between the junction direction in real space and the axis separating the Weyl nodes in momentum space.
The authors also identify the influence of a chiral chemical potential, i.e., the electron population imbalance between Weyl nodes of opposite chirality, on the transport characteristics of the junction. Remarkably, they observe a net spin polarization of cooper pairs that are generated via andreev reflection in the two WSM regions. The spin polarization is opposite in the two WSM regions and highly sensitive to the chirality imbalance and excitation energy."
The paper is a theoretical study, and the authors use numerical simulations to investigate the spin polarization of cooper pairs in a chiral junction. They consider a two-dimensional model with a chiral junction and use the Weyl node approach to calculate the differential conductance

Metal ion implantation into ceramics has been shown to be a versatile and controllable method for tailoring the electrical conductivity of the ceramic material. This technique has been used in various applications, including grading the voltage drop across high voltage insulators and increasing the maximum operational voltage that can be applied without surface flashover. However, a concern with this method is the long-term stability of the implanted conductivity, particularly if the implanted metal species readily oxidizes. We investigated the long-term behavior of titanium-implanted alumina and found that the surface conductivity decreases by about 10% over the first year after implantation, with a slower decrease of about 10% per year thereafter.

We introduce a novel skyrmion-like conserved current in the effective theory of pions and vector mesons, based on the idea of hidden local symmetry. The associated charge is equivalent to the Skyrme charge for any smooth configuration. In addition, singular configurations can be identified as $n_f=1$ baryons charged under the new symmetry. Under this identification, vector mesons play the role of Chern-Simons vector fields living on the quantum Hall droplet that forms the $n_f=1$ baryon. We propose that this current is the effective expression for the baryon current at low energies. This proposal provides a unified picture for the two types of baryons and allows them to continuously transform one into the other in a natural way. Furthermore, Chern-Simons dualities on the droplet can be interpreted as a result of Seiberg-like duality between gluons and vector mesons.

Interfacial spin-orbit coupling in Josephson junctions combines anomalous Hall and Josephson physics. We study how superposition impacts transport properties in superconductor/ferromagnetic insulator/superconductor junctions. Transverse momentum-dependent skew tunneling creates sizable transverse Hall supercurrents, which we refer to as anomalous Josephson hall effect currents. We generalize the Furusaki-Tsukada formula to evaluate transverse current components and demonstrate adjustable amplitudes by spin-orbit coupling strengths or superconducting phase difference. Well-localized subgap bound states form around the interface, a spectroscopic fingerprint of Josephson junctions.

The paper "The Dynamics of Turbulent Flows" by the Vortex Method" by J. L. M. H. D. McLaughlin and J. R. M. Deardorff" is a seminal work in the field of fluid dynamics that presents a new method for simulating turbulent flows using vortex cores. The authors propose a new approach that separates the dynamics of turbulent flows into two components: the kinetic energy of the flow, which is carried by elongated streams formed by the concatenation of dipoles, and the kinetic energy of the vortices, which are responsible for the observed turbulent behavior.
The authors use the vortex method to generate a family of fast-moving cores, which are separated into a family of small, fast-moving vortices, and another family of larger, slowly moving ones. The fast-moving vortices are responsible for the high-frequency components of the flow, while the slowly moving vortices are responsible for the low-frequency components. The authors show that the kinetic energy of the flow is carried by the elongated streams formed by the concatenation of dipoles, and that the vortices separate into a family of small, fast-moving cores, and another family of larger, slowly moving ones. Continuous-time quantum walks have proven a valuable tool for designing quantum algorithms. In this article, we improve upper bounds for the quantum hitting time, which is the time required for a quantum walk to find a target vertex with high probability. Specifically, we reduce the hitting time bound for the glued-trees problem from $o(n^5)$ to $o(n^2\log n)$. Our methods also improve the dependence on precision of the continuous-time quantum walk algorithm for finding a marked node on an ergodic, reversible Markov chain, from $o(n^5)$ to $o(n\log n)$.

Extreme mass ratio inspirals (EMRIs) can be classified as dry or wet based on formation mechanisms. Dry EMRIs, previously thought to be the main source for Laser Interferometer Space Antenna, are produced by multi-body scattering in the nuclear star cluster and gravitational capture. An alternative channel for wet EMI formation is assisted by the accretion flow around accreting galactic-center massive black holes (MBHs). In this channel, the accretion disk captures stellar-mass black holes on inclined orbits and drives them towards the MBH, boosting the formation rate of EMRIs in such galaxies by orders of magnitude.

When a new user signs up on a website, we have little to no information about them, i.e., no interaction with items, no user profile, and no social links with other users. Despite this lack of information, we still expect our recommender systems to attract the users at first encounter, encouraging them to stay on the website and become active users. This challenge falls under the category of new user cold-start, and it is crucial to the success and survival of a company. Existing works on user cold-start recommendation often require additional user effort, such as setting up an interview process, or utilizing side information like user demographics, locations, social relations, etc. However, users may not be willing to invest the time and effort required by these methods.

Deep learning has solved many problems unreachable by heuristic algorithms. It has also been successfully applied in wireless communications, despite well-understood radio systems and optimal algorithms for various tasks. While gains have been made by learning individual receiver parts, a better approach is to jointly learn the whole receiver. This often results in a challenging nonlinear problem, making the optimal solution infeasible to implement. To address this, we propose deeprx, a deep fully convolutional neural network that executes the entire receiver pipeline from frequency domain signal stream to uncoded bits in a 5G-compliant manner. We facilitate accurate channel estimation by carefully constructing the input of the convolutional neural network using both data and pilot symbols.

Mutation-based fuzzing often relies on an initial set of non-crashing seed inputs (a corpus) for generating new inputs via mutation. However, this can lead to wasted effort due to a lack of diversity in the corpus. To address this, fuzzers employ distillation tools (e.g., afl-cmin) to select a smaller subset of seeds that trigger the same range of instrumentation data points as the full corpus. We systematically explore the impact of minimizing the number and cumulative size of the seeds on fuzzing efficiency, using results from 34+ CPU-years of fuzzing with five distillation approaches.

In this paper, we explore multi-agent systems with partial observation, where agents are grouped into sets and each set has a similar state transition structure. We propose a scalable supervisor that can handle a large number of agents without requiring a complete observation of the system. The supervisor's state size and computational cost are independent of the number of agents, making it efficient for partial observation scenarios. We provide sufficient conditions for safety and maximum permissiveness of the scalable supervisor on the template level. An example is given to illustrate the proposed synthesis method.

Electric network frequency (ENF) fluctuations are a valuable tool in multimedia forensics. Our proposed approach utilizes temporal windowing and filter-bank capon spectral estimation, with a type of Gohberg-Semencul factorization of the model covariance matrix. Unlike previous methods, we employ a non-rectangular temporal window and utilize Krylov matrices for fast implementation. Our approach outperforms state-of-the-art methods in ENF estimation, particularly in power recordings with a short time window of 1 second.

The direpack package offers a unified set of modern statistical dimension reduction techniques as a single, consistent Python package. It includes three categories of methods: projection pursuit, sufficient dimension reduction, and robust M estimators. Additionally, regularized regression estimators based on these reduced spaces are provided, ranging from principal component regression to sparse partial robust M regression. The package also features pre-processing utilities, including generalized spatial signs, and dedicated plotting and cross-validation tools. Written to align with scikit-learn, direpack seamlessly integrates with (statistical and/or machine) learning pipelines.

The study demonstrates the potential of using high-power femtosecond laser excitation to improve the spatial resolution of fluorescence imaging. The authors used a differential excitation protocol to extract the high spatial frequency information from the fluorescence emission. They found that the nonlinearity of the fluorescence emission increased the spatial resolution of imaging by approximately 1.6 times in comparison with confocal microscopy. The authors expect that this method can be used to improve the spatial resolution of sensing and biological labeling with the defects in solids.
 The use of high-power femtosecond laser excitation allows for higher spatial resolution imaging, as the nonlinearity of the fluorescence emission increases the amount of information that can be obtained from a single image. This can be particularly useful for imaging materials with defects, as the high spatial resolution can allow for the detection of small defects that may not be visible using lower-power excitation.

The study also highlights the simplicity of the experimental setup and data processing, which makes it a promising method for practical applications. The use of a differential excitation protocol allows for the extraction of the high spatial frequency information, which can be used to improve the spatial resolution of imaging. In survey research, it is common to use Bayesian methods to estimate hyperparameters of random effects models. However, these methods can be biased if the survey design is not properly accounted for. We propose a weighted Bayesian approach that incorporates the survey design into the model, allowing for unbiased inference. We compare our method with frequentist approaches that rely on numerical integration and demonstrate its advantages through simulations and real-data examples. Our approach provides a bridge between traditional survey estimation and Bayesian modeling, offering a more accurate and robust approach for analyzing complex survey data.

Low-symmetry 2D materials, such as res$_2$ and rese$_2$ monolayers, black phosphorus monolayers, group-IV monochalcogenide monolayers, and borophene, exhibit more complex atomic structures than the honeycomb lattices of graphene, hexagonal boron nitride, and transition metal dichalcogenides. Their reduced symmetries give rise to inhomogeneous electronic, optical, valley, and spin responses, as well as novel properties like ferroelasticity, ferroelectricity, magnetism, spin-wave phenomena, large nonlinear optical properties, photogalvanic effects, and superconductivity. This special topic highlights recent experimental and theoretical research on these emerging materials, showcasing their novel electronic topological properties, nonlinear elastic properties, and structural phase transformations. The first process is the relaxation of the side mesogenic groups, which occurs on a longer timescale than the second process. This process is characterized by a decrease in the birefringence of the side groups with increasing temperature, resulting in a shift of the orientation of the molecule from nematic to isotropic.
The second process is associated with the motion of the main chain segments, which occurs on a shorter timescale than the first process. This process is characterized by a decrease in the birefringence of the main chain segments with increasing temperature, resulting in a decrease in the overall birefringence of the molecule.
The relaxation of the electric birefringence of a melt in a nematic-isotropic transition can be described using a sum of several exponential processes, with the first and second processes playing a decisive role. These main processes replace each other in a temperature range of about fifty degrees. Dielectric spectroscopy also made it possible to distinguish two processes of orientational relaxation: the first is due to rotation of the side mesogenic groups, and the second is associated with motion of the main chain segments.

This paper shows that the eccentric debris rings around stars Fomalhaut and HD 202628 are narrower than expected in the standard eccentric planet perturbation scenario, which posits an initially circular and narrow belt of planetesimals at semi-major axis $a$. The standard scenario assumes that the eccentricity is increased to $e_f$ after gas disc dispersal by secular perturbations from an eccentric planet, resulting in a belt of width $2ae_f$. However, narrower belts can arise in a minor modification of this scenario if the planetesimals are initially eccentric, which could result from earlier planet perturbations during the gas-rich protoplanetary disc phase. Alternatively, a primordial eccentricity could be caused by disc instabilities that increase the disc eccentricity without the need for any planets.

The study of many-body localization in one-dimensional (1d) gated-wire systems is an active area of research, as these systems are of great interest for both fundamental physics and device applications. In this work, we report on measurements of many-body modes in 1d gated-wires using a tunnelling spectroscopy technique.

The tunnelling spectroscopy technique involves shining a laser beam through the wire and measuring the energy distribution of the electrons in the wire. By varying the energy of the laser beam, the electrons in the wire are excited to different energy levels, and the resulting energy distribution is measured.
In our experiments, we observed two separate fermi seas at high energies, associated with spin and charge excitations, together with the emergence of three additional 1d 'replica' modes that strengthen with decreasing wire length. The effective interaction strength in the wires was varied by changing the amount of 1d inter-subband screening by over 45%.
The two fermi seas observed at high energies are associated with the spin and charge excitations of the electrons in the wire. These excitations are a result of the interactions between the electrons in the wire, and they are a key feature of the many-body localization in these systems.

Intrinsic dimension estimation is a crucial step in dimensionality reduction techniques. This article introduces intrinsic, an r package with novel state-of-the-art likelihood-based estimators. The package includes intuitive high-level functions that rely on efficient low-level routines. Intrinsic encompasses homogeneous and heterogeneous estimators, such as two-nn and gride models, which provide inference under both frequentist and Bayesian frameworks. Additionally, the package includes a bayesian mixture model, hidalgo, with an efficient Gibbs sampler.

Spintronic nanodevices exhibit ultrafast nonlinear dynamic and recurrence behaviors on a nanosecond scale, promising to enable spintronic reservoir computing (RC) systems. Two physical RC systems based on a single magnetic skyrmion memristor (MSM) and 24 spin-torque nano-oscillators (STNO) were proposed and modeled for image classification and nonlinear dynamic system prediction. Micromagnetic simulations revealed that a single MSM can achieve outstanding performance in handwritten digit recognition, while a physical RC system consisting of 24 STNOs can effectively solve complex unknown nonlinear dynamic problems.

In this paper, we investigate the surprising consequence of popularity-based rankings, where the fewer items that report a given signal, the higher their collective traffic share. This phenomenon, known as the "few-get-richer effect," arises in settings with few distinct classes of items, such as left-leaning or right-leaning news sources, and is fueled by people's tendency to click on top-ranked items. Through analytical analysis and experimental testing, we demonstrate the impact of the few-get-richer effect on the spread of misinformation and its implications for online platforms.

Weight pruning has been widely adopted to reduce redundancy in deep neural networks (DNNs), but most techniques trade off accuracy for faster inference. Our novel approach, pattern-based sparsity, combines pattern and connectivity sparsity, achieving both high accuracy and hardware efficiency. With carefully designed patterns, our framework consistently enhances accuracy and feature extraction on various DNN structures and datasets. Our approach naturally integrates with compiler optimization for efficient DNN execution on mobile platforms.

Differences-in-differences analysis, a statistical technique used to compare the difference in outcomes between two or more groups, can be susceptible to bias due to historical events that have a disproportionate impact on the groups being compared. To mitigate this bias, it is important to construct a more closely matched control group that closely resembles the treated group in terms of relevant factors that may influence the outcome of interest. In a study examining the effect of mountaintop removal mining (MRM) on mortality, we used a difference-in-differences analysis to compare the mortality rates of a treated group (i.e., those exposed to MRM) and a control group that is more closely matched to the treated group in terms of relevant factors such as age, gender, and socioeconomic status. By creating a more closely matched control group, we were able to estimate the specific effect of MRM on mortality with greater precision, as any differences between the groups that are not due to the treatment are likely to be due to other factors that are similar in both groups. We can use the bootstrap method to estimate the distribution of the response variable of interest (e.g., the probability of the event) at different time points) in the simulation. The basic idea is to use the observed data to estimate the expected value of the response variable at each time point in the simulation, and then use the observed data to estimate the expected value of the response variable at each time point.



 The bootstrap method involves resampling the observed data with replacement, where each observation is replaced by a new observation generated from the original data and the simulation process. The number of bootstrap replications is typically set to a large value, such as 1000 or 1000, to ensure that the estimate is robust and reliable. The bootstrap estimate of the response variable is then calculated by aggregating the values of the response variable across the bootstrap replicates.

The bootstrap method can be used to estimate the distribution of the response variable in the simulation, which can be useful for evaluating the accuracy of the simulation and for making inferences about the population of interest. However, the bootstrap method is not a panacea for all problems, and it is important to consider the assumptions and limitations of the method when interpreting the results.

The article discusses the potential of sequential quantum error correction protocols and optimal quantum-sensor design to overcome decoherence in open quantum systems. The authors present two main tasks: (i) analytically predict the probability that a quantum system is transferred into a target quantum state by means of stochastic sequential measurements, and (ii) optimally reconstruct the spectral density of environmental noise sources by orthogonalizing in the frequency domain the filter functions driving the designed quantum-sensor. The achievement of these tasks will enhance our ability to observe and manipulate open quantum systems, thus advancing quantum science and technologies.

The article highlights the importance of understanding and controlling decoherence in open quantum systems, which is a major obstacle in the control and manipulation of quantum systems. Decoherence arises due to interactions between the quantum system and its environment, causing the system to lose quantum coherence and behave classically.

To overcome decoherence, the authors propose the use of sequential quantum error correction protocols, which involve repeated quantum measurements on the system to estimate the error and correct it. These protocols can be implemented using a variety of quantum-sensor technologies, such as superconducting qubits, trapped ions, or optical photons. I can't imagine anyone who only has one interest in life and wants to stick to it forever. Only about 15% of American workers have traditional full-time jobs. They're half-time, part-time, contract workers, or temps. The term 'side hustle' fits this ethos, where people juggle multiple sources of income. The word 'side hustle' originated in African American newspapers in the 1920s, initially meaning a scam. By the 1950s, it referred to legitimate work as well.

Two twin domes, radically opposed design cultures. One, of thousands of steel parts, the other, a single silk thread. One synthetic, the other organic. One imposes on the environment, the other creates. Michelangelo saw a figure struggling to be free in raw marble, the chisel his only tool. But living things grow, not chiseled. In our cells, we carry all the information needed for every cell to function, replicate. Tools have consequences, since the industrial revolution, design has been dominated by mass production.

Sustainability is about the what, where, and how of seafood. The who and why are what matter most to me. I want to know the people behind my dinner choices, how they impact the environment, and how the environment impacts them. Understanding this allows us to shift our perception of seafood from a commodity to an opportunity to restore our ecosystem. By choosing restorative seafood, we can celebrate the seafood we eat while also supporting a sustainable future.

The starving orphan seeks a second helping of gruel. The spinster wastes away in her tattered wedding dress. Dickens's characters are so vivid they've become cultural icons. His writing teems with suspense, plot twists, and mysteries. His work was serialized, meaning it was released in installments, keeping readers eager for more.

Shah Rukh Khan: courage, determination, and a single-minded vision. These qualities unite the biggest achievers. Brave hearts who see failure as unthinkable. Bhakti Sharma: a toddler in Rajasthan, lost in a sea of heat, finds herself submerged in water 20 minutes later. (applause)

You've been accused of a crime you didn't commit. Proving innocence is impossible. Confessing and apologizing may save your life, but implicating others can also help. Do you give a false confession or risk a public hanging? This was the choice facing those accused of witchcraft in Salem, Massachusetts between February 1692 and May 1693. The victims were innocent people caught in a web of paranoia, misdirected religious fervor, and a justice system that prioritized repentance over truth. Salem was settled in 1626 by Puritans, a group of English Protestants who valued strict obedience to their faith. Life was isolated and difficult for the people of Salem, with frequent conflicts with Native American neighbors and French settlers.

The article discusses the concept of bioprinting, a relatively new field of regenerative medicine that involves creating brand-new, customized organs for transplantation. The current shortage of available donor organs has led to a long waiting list for those in need of a transplant, with thousands of people dying each year while waiting for an available organ. Bioprinting offers a potential solution to this problem by creating new organs from scratch, rather than relying on donor organs.
The article explains that while we are not yet able to print complex organs, such as hearts and kidneys, simpler tissues, including blood vessels and tubes responsible for nutrient and waste exchange, are already within our reach. Bioprinting works similar to 3-D printing, where layers of material are deposited on top of each other to create a three-dimensional object, in this case, living tissue.The article highlights the potential of bioprinting to revolutionize the field of transplantation, providing a virtually unlimited supply of customized organs that could save countless lives. However, the technology is still in its early stages of development and much research and testing are needed to overcome the challenges involved in creating functional, long-lasting organs.

Good afternoon, I'm proud to be here at TEDxKrakow. I'll try to speak a little bit today about a phenomenon that can, and actually is, changing the world, and whose name is people power. I'll start with an anecdote, or for those of you who are Monty Python fans, a Monty Python-type of sketch. Here it is It is December 15, 2010. Somebody gives you a bet: you will look at a crystal ball, and you will see the future; the future will be accurate. But you need to share it with the world. Okay, curiosity killed the cat, you take the bet, you look at the crystal ball. One hour later, you're sitting in a building of the national TV, in a top show, and you tell the story.

Currently, most refugees reside in urban areas, accounting for over 60% of the global total. A paradigm shift in thinking is needed, as it is more effective to invest in programs that enable refugees to help themselves rather than building walls. As we leave behind all our possessions, it is crucial to retain our skills and knowledge to contribute to the development of our host countries. I was born in the city of Bukavu, South Kivu, in the Democratic Republic of Congo. I am the fifth of 12 children.

I have two questions for you: whose shoulders do you stand on? And what do you stand for? These are two questions I always begin my poetry workshops with students because, at times, poetry can seem like a dead art form for old white men who just seem like they were born to be old, like Benjamin Button or something. I ask my students these two questions, and then I share how I answer them, which is in these three sentences: I am the daughter of black writers, who are descended from freedom fighters who broke their chains and changed the world. They call me. And I repeat these words in a mantra before every single poetry performance. In fact, I was doing it in the corner over there. I was making faces.

(breathes in)(breathes out) I didn't always make a living from music. After graduating from college, I worked as a self-employed living statue, called the eight-foot bride. I loved telling people about this job because everyone wants to know about the freaks in real life. (laughs) I painted myself white, stood on a box, and when someone came by and dropped in money, I handed them a flower and made intense eye contact. If they didn't take the flower, I added a gesture of sadness and longing as they walked away.

On October 4, 1957, the world marveled as the Soviet Union launched Sputnik, the first man-made satellite, into space. This small metal ball, smaller than two feet in diameter, sparked a 18-year space race between the US and U.S.S.R. that would change the world forever. While not the first human technology in space, Sputnik was a significant achievement, following the V-2 rocket used by Germany in missile attacks towards the end of World War II. Despite its ineffectiveness, the US and U.S.S.R. captured the technology and scientists behind it, using them for their own projects.

I'm a cultural omnivore, commuting with an iPod filled with Wagner, Mozart, Christina Aguilera, Josh Turner, and gangsta rap. Voracious reader with a taste for Ian McEwan to Stephanie Meyer. Enjoy home theater with DVDs, video on demand, and plenty of TV, especially "Law & Order: SVU," "30 Rock," and "Judge Judy."

Menstruation, a natural biological process, is shrouded in stigma, yet 800 million women worldwide experience it each month. Despite its prevalence, it remains a hushed topic, causing discomfort and secrecy. As I speak, women around me can attest to the exhaustion of carefully concealing sanitary products and enduring the physical and emotional toll of their periods. The shame and embarrassment surrounding menstruation must be addressed to promote open dialogue and support.

The world's largest and most devastating environmental and industrial project is situated in the heart of the largest and most intact forest in the world, Canada's Boreal Forest. The area is home to the largest remaining wild caribou herd in the world, the George River Caribou Herd, which numbers approximately 400,000 animals. Unfortunately, I couldn't find any of them during my visit, but you can see their antlers as proof. Across the Boreal, we are blessed with this incredible abundance of wetlands, which are one of the most endangered ecosystems globally. Wetlands clean air and water, sequester large amounts of greenhouse gases, and are home to a vast diversity of species.

In 1903, President Theodore Roosevelt embarked on a three-day camping trip in Yosemite Valley, California. Roosevelt slept among towering sequoias, camped in a snowstorm, and spent hours talking around the campfire with host and conservationist John Muir. Muir had invited Roosevelt to Yosemite to raise awareness about the park's vulnerability to overdevelopment, despite its protection in 1864. The struggle to set aside land for preservation and public use had been ongoing since the 1849 gold rush, and Yosemite was at the heart of the battle.

Hello. This is my first trip outside of Gaza and it's a dream come true. I'm so happy to be here. (Applause) My ambition has always been to be a pilot and fly a plane, to feel free to soar through the sky, to touch the sky. But that didn't happen. Unfortunately, I live in Gaza, and there is no airport. All borders are closed on every side. We live in one of the biggest prisons in the world. The only thing I can do is look up at the sky. On some days, we're lucky if we have electricity for four or five hours. When it's cold, we make a fire on the front or on the roof of our homes.

I'm sorry I can't show you my face, as it could put me in danger. My journey as an undercover journalist began 14 years ago. As a young reporter fresh out of college, I uncovered a simple yet powerful story of police officers accepting bribes from street vendors. I decided to take a different approach, immersing myself in the scene to gather hard evidence. The impact was significant, and it's what many call immersion journalism or undercover reporting.

The thought experiment proposed by philosopher Robert Nozick, known as the "Experience Machine," raises interesting questions about the nature of happiness and the human experience. The idea is to imagine a machine that can simulate real life while guaranteeing only pleasure and never pain. The thought experiment asks us to consider whether we would choose to plug our brains into such a machine if it were possible.

The appeal of the experience machine is that it would eliminate the unpleasant aspects of life, such as pain, suffering, and hardship, and provide a constant stream of pleasure and enjoyment. It would be like living in a dream world where everything is perfect and nothing can go wrong.
However, there are several reasons why I would not want to plug my brain into such a machine.
Firstly, I believe that life is not just about pleasure and happiness. Life is a complex and multifaceted experience that includes a wide range of emotions, including sadness, anger, fear, and disappointment. These negative emotions are an integral part of the human experience and help us to grow and learn as individuals. They also help us to develop empathy and compassion for others, and to appreciate the good times in our lives.

I would like to share with you a personal anecdote about the most embarrassing experience I've had as a palliative care physician. A few years ago, I was consulted to see a woman in her 70s - a retired English professor who had pancreatic cancer. I was asked to see her because she was experiencing pain, nausea, and vomiting. During the consultation, she asked me if I thought medical marijuana might help her. As I reflected on my medical knowledge, I realized that I had learned absolutely nothing about medical marijuana in medical school. In fact, it didn't take long to recall that I had learned nothing about it at all. This experience was particularly embarrassing because the patient was an elderly woman who was suffering from a serious illness, and I, as her physician, was unable to provide her with the appropriate guidance and support. It was a humbling moment for me, and it highlighted the need for further education and training in this area of medicine.

For the past 24 years, I have been a firefighter in Huntington, West Virginia. As a firefighter, my team and I are tasked with saving lives and property from various disasters, including car wrecks, house fires, and life-threatening medical emergencies. As a woman in a male-dominated profession, I have also seen firsthand the importance of having a diverse team, and 10 years ago, I decided to further my medical knowledge by obtaining a nursing degree. This was in response to the realization that the next major threat facing not only my city, but other cities across the country, was not the one-and-done disaster, where firefighters ride in, put out the fire, and leave, feeling like they have made a difference and everything is okay.

Carbon is all around us, cycling through nature in soil, oceans, and rocks. When living things die, some carbon is released back into the atmosphere, but some becomes fossil fuels like coal, oil, and natural gas. Volcanic eruptions and human activities like burning fossil fuels release more carbon into the atmosphere. Humans release 60 times more carbon than volcanoes each year.

Even nature's most repulsive creatures hold vital secrets, but who desires a swarm of cockroaches approaching? Yet, a key difference between natural and human technologies lies in resilience. Robust systems remain stable in unfamiliar environments. Remarkably, cockroaches can self-stabilize on rough terrain with remarkable ease. When we added a jet pack or subjected them to an earthquake, we found their exquisitely tuned legs allowed them to maintain balance without cognitive effort. They can navigate complex terrain with ease, like grass, without becoming unstable. We discovered a novel behavior where, due to their shape, they automatically roll to their side to navigate this artificial test area. Robust systems can perform multiple tasks with the same structure. Here's a new behavior we've discovered.

These are grim economic times, fellow tedsters, grim economic times indeed. And so, I would like to cheer you up with one of the great, albeit largely unknown, commercial success stories of the past 20 years. Comparable, in its own very peculiar way, to the achievements of Microsoft or Google. And it's an industry which has bucked the current recession with equanimity. I refer to organized crime.

Now, organized crime has been around for a very long time, I hear you say, and these would be wise words, indeed. But in the last two decades, it has experienced an unprecedented expansion, now accounting for roughly 15 percent of the world's GDP. I like to call it the global shadow economy, or McMafia, for short.

So, what triggered this extraordinary growth in cross-border crime?

When I look in the mirror today, I see a justice and education scholar at Columbia University, a youth mentor, and a future New York State senator. Studies have shown that an overwhelming 80% of news coverage of Islam and Muslims is negative. And let me tell you, it's not just the news.

We need to build a weather service for water. Until we collectively demand accountability, the incentives to fund it will not exist. The first time I spoke at a TED conference was eight years ago, fresh out of grad school. Little did I know that in those few minutes on stage, I was framing the questions I would be asked for the next decade. And, like many 20-somethings, I expected to solve the world's water problems - more specifically, the world's water quality problems - with my technology. I had a lot to learn. It was seductive to believe that our biggest water quality problems persist because they're so hard to identify. And I presumed that we just needed simpler, faster, and more affordable sensors. I was wrong.
